docs.lead_paragraph: I was just five years old when the vibe in my grandmother Nannie’s kitchen aroused my culinary curiosity. It took 30 years and a dozen other hidden figures of the food world for me to appreciate the kitchen as a site for social change.

headline.main: How the Women of the Jemima Code Freed Me

docs.abstract: I started filming the protests in New York so I could draw attention to the realities of black America that I was first exposed to during my military service.
docs.snippet: I started filming the protests in New York so I could draw attention to the realities of black America that I was first exposed to during my military service.
docs.lead_paragraph: I’m in film school, using the last bit of my G.I. Bill, and have been shooting a short film about five black artists surviving Covid-19. We wrapped shooting on the morning of Memorial Day, and that afternoon George Floyd was killed. A few days later, one of the artists I’m profiling headed to the streets in Brooklyn to protest, and it just felt like the responsible thing to show up with my camera and capture the stories.

headline.main: Serving in the Army as a Queer Black Man Opened My Eyes to Racism in America

docs.abstract: He was a Princeton-educated corporate lawyer. She provided legal services for the poor. Now they are accused in a Molotov cocktail attack on a police car.
docs.snippet: He was a Princeton-educated corporate lawyer. She provided legal services for the poor. Now they are accused in a Molotov cocktail attack on a police car.
docs.lead_paragraph: The day before he went out to protest, Colinford Mattis, 32, an Ivy-educated corporate lawyer in Brooklyn, chatted for over an hour on the phone with a close high school friend. They discussed George Floyd’s death as just “another example of an unarmed black person being killed,” the friend said, but they talked about grocery shopping and YouTube videos as well.

headline.main: The 2 Lawyers, the Anti-Police Protests and the Molotov Cocktail Attack
